{"award_age":89.0,"bio_image":"full\/ea1db004d3452da06dbeb7df125068c571b3b7f8.jpg","category":"Economics","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1923-06-02T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":null,"gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/4\/40\/Shapley%2C_Lloyd_%281923%29.jpeg\/220px-Shapley%2C_Lloyd_%281923%29.jpeg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Lloyd_S._Shapley","mini_bio":"<p><b>Lloyd Stowell Shapley<\/b> (born June 2, 1923) is a distinguished <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_States\" title=\"United States\">American<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Mathematician\" title=\"Mathematician\">mathematician<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize\" title=\"Nobel Prize\">Nobel Prize<\/a>\u2013winning <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Economist\" title=\"Economist\">economist<\/a>. He is a Professor Emeritus at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_California,_Los_Angeles\" title=\"University of California, Los Angeles\">University of California, Los Angeles<\/a> (<a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/UCLA\" title=\"UCLA\" class=\"mw-redirect\">UCLA<\/a>), affiliated with departments of Mathematics and Economics. He has contributed to the fields of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Mathematical_economics\" title=\"Mathematical economics\">mathematical economics<\/a> and especially <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Game_theory\" title=\"Game theory\">game theory<\/a>. Since the work of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_von_Neumann\" title=\"John von Neumann\">von Neumann<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Oskar_Morgenstern\" title=\"Oskar Morgenstern\">Morgenstern<\/a> in 1940s, Shapley has been regarded by many experts as the very personification of game theory.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Lloyd_S._Shapley#cite_note-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Lloyd_S._Shapley#cite_note-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Lloyd_S._Shapley#cite_note-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> With <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Alvin_E._Roth\" title=\"Alvin E. Roth\">Alvin E. Roth<\/a>, Shapley won the 2012 <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Memorial_Prize_in_Economic_Sciences\" title=\"Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences\">Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences<\/a> \"for the theory of stable allocations and the practice of market design.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Lloyd_S._Shapley#cite_note-4\"><span>[<\/span>4<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p>","name":"Lloyd S. Shapley","place_of_birth":"Cambridge, Massachusetts","place_of_death":null,"text":"Lloyd S. Shapley , Economics, 2012","year":2012.0}